To create a Rust application that supports the Eleven Labs API and reads the contents of the clipboard aloud using Text-to-Speech (TTS), you can follow these steps:

1. Install Rust:
   Follow the instructions on the official Rust website to install Rust: https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install

2. Create a new Rust project:
   Open a terminal and run the following command to create a new Rust project:

   ```
   cargo new elevenlabs_tts --bin
   ```

3. Add dependencies:
   In the `Cargo.toml` file, add the following dependencies:

   ```toml
   [dependencies]
   reqwest = { version = "0.11", features = ["json"] }
   serde = { version = "1.0", features = ["derive"] }
   serde_json = "1.0"
   clipboard = "3.0"
   tokio = { version = "1.17", features = ["full"] }
   ```

4. Implement the main function:
   Create a new file named `src/main.rs` and add the following code:

   ```rust
   use reqwest::Client;
   use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
   use clipboard::ClipboardProvider;
   use std::env;
   use tokio::task::spawn_blocking;

   #[tokio::main]
   async fn main() {
       let api_key = env::var("ELEVEN_LABS_API_KEY").expect("API key not found");
       let clipboard = ClipboardProvider::new().unwrap();
       let text = clipboard.get_contents().unwrap();

       let response = spawn_blocking(move || {
           let client = Client::new();
           let url = "https://api.elevenlabs.io/v1/text-to-speech/synthesize";
           let data = serde_json::json!({
               "text": text,
               "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-A",
               "ssml": false
           });

           let req = client.post(url)
               .header("Authorization", format!("Bearer {}", api_key))
               .json(&data)
               .send()
               .expect("Failed to send request");

           let response = req.json::<Response>().expect("Failed to parse response");

           response.audio
       })
       .await
       .expect("Failed to run blocking task");

       // Save the audio data to a file
       let mut file = std::fs::File::create("output.mp3").expect("Failed to create file");
       file.write_all(&response).expect("Failed to write audio data");

       // Play the audio file using a media player
       // (This step is platform-specific and requires additional libraries)
   }

   #[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Debug)]
   struct Response {
       audio: Vec<u8>,
       // Other fields...
   }
   ```

5. Set the API key as an environment variable:
   Replace `ELEVEN_LABS_API_KEY` in the code above with your actual API key from Eleven Labs. You can set the API key as an environment variable on your system or in your IDE.

6. Save the files and run the application:
   In the terminal, navigate to the project directory and run the following command:

   ```
   cargo run
   ```

   The application will read the contents of the clipboard, synthesize the text using the Eleven Labs API, save the audio data to a file, and (optionally) play the audio file using a media player.
